Ambroſe writes of the deſire, and vowed reſolution of Baptiſme in Valentinian, that being diſappointed, by providence, of the Act thereof, in reſpect of the outward ſigne, yet God giving him the grace of that Sacrament, he was accepted as a Chriſtian;
and as S. James ſpeaking of Abraham's attempt in offering his onely Son, upon a Divine command, ſtyleth it anJam 2.21. actuall offering of him, for that in the ſerious preparation of his minde, he really, and fiduciarily intended it, though the ſtory acquaints us, that the thing it ſelfe wasGen. 22. 11, 12. prevented by an heavenly Angel: ſo the indefatigable endeavours of this pious undertaker are interpreted, as a full diſpatch of that work, by his gracious God,
